data.content:
Here's the full migration. The code has three `Thread.Abort`-related patterns:

| Pattern | .NET Framework | ASP.NET Core replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Aborts the thread to stop response | Just return from the action |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | Redirect + abort thread | Return `Redirect()` result |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Swallow expected abort | Remove entirely — no abort happens |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Text;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Return a FileResult — the framework handles headers and response lifecycle.
        // No Response.Clear/Write/End needed; action results replace all of that.
        return File(
            Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Just return a RedirectResult — no thread abort, no endResponse flag.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No catch (ThreadAbortException) — it cannot occur in modern .NET.
        // Thread.Abort throws PlatformNotSupportedException on .NET 6+.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() { /* ... */ return ""; }
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key pitfalls to watch for

**1. Don't replicate the old `Response.Write` pattern:**
```csharp
// ❌ BAD — porting the old style literally
Response.ContentType = "text/csv";
await Response.Body.WriteAsync(bytes);
return; // nothing stops further middleware from running

// ✅ GOOD — return an action result; framework owns the response
return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
```

**2. `User.Identity` can be null in ASP.NET Core:**
```csharp
// ❌ BAD — NullReferenceException if no auth middleware configured
if (!User.Identity.IsAuthenticated)

// ✅ GOOD — null-conditional check
if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
```

**3. Don't catch `OperationCanceledException` and swallow it** — in ASP.NET Core, `HttpContext.RequestAborted` fires this when a client disconnects. Let it propagate so the framework handles it:
```csharp
// ❌ BAD — replaces the old ThreadAbortException swallow with a new antipattern
catch (OperationCanceledException) { }

// ✅ GOOD — only catch if you need specific cleanup, then re-throw
catch (OperationCanceledException) when (needsCleanup)
{
    RollbackPartialWork();
    throw;
}
```

**4. For long-running report generation**, pass the cancellation token so work stops if the client disconnects:
```csharp
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> Export(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core automatically binds HttpContext.RequestAborted here
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    return File(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data), "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

**5. The `[Authorize]` attribute replaces manual auth checks:**
```csharp
// ❌ Manually checking auth + redirecting (old Web Forms pattern)
if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
    return Redirect("/login");

// ✅ Let the framework handle it declaratively
[Authorize]
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult Redirect() { /* ... */ }
// Unauthenticated users are redirected automatically via auth middleware config
```

## Summary of what was removed and why

| Removed | Reason |
|---|---|
| `Response.Clear()` | Action results own the full response — nothing to clear |
| `Response.Write(data)` | Replaced by `File()` action result |
| `Response.End()` | No equivalent needed — returning from the action ends the response |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | Replaced by `return Redirect(url)` — the `true`/endResponse concept doesn't exist |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+; this catch would never fire |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | `File()` result sets `Content-Disposition` automatically |
